##World Health Organization, former director of infectious diseases, said: It is too early to say that the virus will infect two thirds of the world's population

In response to the prediction made by some scholars that new pneumonia might "infect two-thirds of the world's population, " The WHO's former assistant director general for Infectious Diseases, David Heyman, Professor of epidemiology at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine (LSHTM) , said it was too early to make such a prediction.

Just this past week, as the spread of pneumonia from the COVID-19 spread, said Ella Longini, a WHO consultant and director of the University of Florida, two-thirds of the world's population could be infected.

Longini, who has tracked the spread of the new coronavirus in China, said the virus could eventually infect billions more people than current statistics suggest, the Bloomberg L.P. reported Feb. 13. His model is based on the fact that each infected person usually infects two or three others, and that the spread of the virus is becoming harder to track because of the lack of rapid detection and the relatively mild symptoms of infection in some cases.

Even halving transmission would still infect a third of the world's population, Longini said, and surveillance and containment would be ineffective unless the virus's transmissibility changed, finding and isolating cases will not stop the spread of the virus.

In an interview with Interface News, Professor Hyman said it was too early to make such predictions. We do not yet know the transmissibility of the virus, the extent to which it is easy or difficult to spread, the effectiveness of prevention and control measures taken by countries, the proportion of symptoms or the specific case fatality rate, so there's no answer.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
David Heyman, Source: Wikipedia

Professor Hyman, 74, has been involved in the prevention and treatment of the last three Ebola outbreaks in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and has investigated the spread of infectious diseases such as smallpox and malaria in central and western Africa and South Asia. During the SARS epidemic in 2003, Hyman also represented World Health Organization on the front lines of the epidemic, when he was the WHO's executive director for infectious diseases.

What countries should do now is continue to contain the spread of the virus, reduce people's exposure to the virus, isolate cases and track contacts, Hyman told interface news. China has done much to slow the spread of the disease around the world compared to when it first broke out.

The following is a transcript of the interview, edited for Publication.

Interface News: What do you think of the claim that the new coronavirus could infect two-thirds of the world's population?

HYMAN: I think it's too early, so to speak. That's not enough information.

This is an estimate derived from a model that is still being refined. Now they don't know how contagious the virus is, so there's no answer, and no one can predict what's going to happen. Many countries are doing everything they can to contain the virus and reduce human contact with it. This job should go on.

Interface News: In your opinion, if this virus really infected a large number of the world's population, the proportion of severe and mild illness will be what?

HYMAN: The problem is, we don't know, because we don't know how many mild cases there are.

The cases are initially judged by the presence of symptoms of pneumonia, which are often severe. Last week, China also updated its diagnostic criteria, so it's too early to say how severe the symptoms are, or what the case fatality rate is.

It does, however, show features similar to seasonal flu, except that it is more severe among health care workers. It's good to look at the severity of symptoms, but there are many factors to consider, such as some associated diseases, such as diabetes, lung disease, and so on, and many questions remain about the circumstances of these cases themselves.

Interface News: In your opinion, what are China's measures to contain the outbreak? Is it feasible if other countries do the same?

HYMAN: I think China is doing everything it can to contain the epidemic. These measures can continue, after all, some measures that many countries can not do, such as keeping people at home, but China can, and if it feels that this is the best way, it should continue. I can not judge whether this is right or wrong. This is the strategy China has chosen.

No other country has taken such a step, and most have opted for a workable quarantine, with further communication to find a solution if people are reluctant.

Interface News: Experts from the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention have previously said that transmission in China outside of Hubei Province is mainly on a household basis, not in the community. What do you think?

HYMAN: I hope that's true. If so, it would be easier to contain the outbreak.

Interface News: Now that the first case has been found in Africa, how do you think this will affect the current outbreak overseas?

HYMAN: I don't know. Nobody can predict that now.

Interface News: What advice do you have on how to contain the spread of the epidemic as much as possible? What should countries with weak health systems do?

HYMAN: They should do the same thing as the developed country, which is to isolate cases, track contacts, and tell contacts what to do when they have symptoms like fever, and keep them at arm's length from their families, if they get sick, they should be separated from their families for the first time.

Communities also need to be active in prevention and control efforts to find and isolate patients and care for them, as well as a contact tracking system to keep them under observation for two weeks to see if they develop symptoms such as fever. Communities themselves need to work together to prevent and control the outbreak.

Interface News: Singapore is also taking these measures, but the number of recently confirmed cases in the country is still increasing rapidly. What do you think?

HYMAN: Singapore is doing its best to prevent the disease. During the SARS period, they had the same problem, but in the end it was contained. So I hope China and Singapore can do the same this time.

The diamond princess is now docked at a Japanese port, and there have been some cases of local infection in the country. Some people think that it may face a considerable risk of epidemic spread in the short term. What do you think?

HYMAN: I can't predict what's going to happen next. If I knew what was GONNA happen next, I'd be a magician, and so would you.

Interface News: A study suggests that travel restrictions could have a positive impact on the spread of the epidemic. But even so, cases are emerging in some countries and increasing, particularly in local infections. If these countries do not impose travel restrictions, will their cases be exported to other countries, as they were in the early stages of the epidemic?

HYMAN: It depends on how effective their containment measures are. I can't predict it. It's up to them to stop it, they have a strong health system, they have years of experience in this area, and hopefully they will succeed this time.

But again, no one can predict it, because we don't fully understand how contagious the new coronavirus is. What we now know is that it can spread from person to person, in social situations, in close face-to-face situations, and if you don't pay attention in the hospital, if you don't wash your hands, health care workers are also at risk. But we don't know exactly how contagious the virus is.

We also don't know whether the measures taken by some countries are effective, and everyone hopes they are, but no one knows yet. Countries are now acting on known information about public health and following certain guidelines.

Interface News: Do you think it is necessary for Japan to cancel the Tokyo Olympics?

HYMAN: it's too early to make a decision.

Interface News: Have you seen the inflection point yet?

HYMAN: So far, cases have been reported in 25 countries outside of China. These countries are all working hard on prevention and control, and some have seen some success while others have not, but I hope that eventually all countries will move in the same direction and stop the spread of the epidemic.

Interface News: Is Population Density also a factor? Would it be better, for example, to live in less densely populated countries in Europe and the US?

HYMAN: Yes. If the virus can spread from person to person, the denser the population, the harder it is to control. However, we do not yet know the nature of the virus, do not know how easy or difficult it is to spread, especially in open space, still need to wait and see. Of course, in countries with high population density, the risk of exposure for the general population is higher.

Interface News: What do you know about drugs and vaccines?

HYMAN: Western countries are already working on a vaccine, but it will take at least six to nine months, or a year or more. Now China is also conducting clinical trials of drugs, and a lot of work is being done, which I think is helpful in containing the spread of the epidemic.

I'm not just talking about China's tactics, of course, because they can be seen in other countries as well, but China's situation is much more unique, so China has done quite well.

China has made great efforts to contain the outbreak, especially to stop it from spreading to other countries. China has clearly slowed the global spread of the epidemic since it first broke out. I hope China will do a better job of containing the outbreak at home, as it did during the SARS epidemic.
